<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10062g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10062g">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10062g"> 62(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> magnified dispatches / 1870 Paris D<font color="green">[agron]</font> / 110,000 = 1 gr</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Quelques-uns <font color="green">[= pigeons]</font>, de vieux routiers, rentr&egrave;rent &agrave; Paris quatre, cinq et six fois porteurs de ces merveilleuses d&eacute;p&ecirc;ches dues &agrave; M. Dagron, elles &eacute;taient photographi&eacute;es sur des pellicules si l&eacute;g&egrave;res, que le total des <mark>115.000 d&eacute;p&ecirc;ches</mark> re&ccedil;ues pendant l&apos;investissement de la capitale ne pesait pas, r&eacute;unies &agrave; elles toutes, le poids de <mark>1 gramme</mark>! <font color="green">[Some of the most experienced [pigeons]</font> returned to Paris four, five, or six times, carrying those marvellous dispatches devised by Mr Dagron. These were photographed on film that was so light that the total of 115,000 dispatches received during the siege of the capital did not weigh, when all assembled, more than one gram!] <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 211</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: On the same page an illustration shows the projector used to magnify the dispatches: the legend underneath says &ldquo;Agrandissement des d&eacute;p&ecirc;ches microscopiques &eacute;xp&eacute;di&eacute;es par pigeon.&rdquo;</mm> </dd></dl>
